Dawai: And we also have those here, the four Chokshyaks, right? Those are the four ways of letting be. They're talking about those, but we have the modes of liberation. Sometimes those are presented as the snake, the thief entering an empty house, and the old friend. I'm not going to get into the modes of liberation just yet. Let's see if they do, and we'll go along with it.

[p 166]

>>  Since self-awareness is free from all [thoughts], there are four modes of liberation. Through confidence in liberation with these four key points, the locale of saṃsāra and enlightenment will be free from origin or creation as baseless from the root.

>To elaborate on this meaning, the quote continues:

>>  That which is called "the self-liberated mind" has not gone from one state to another. This mind devoid of having been bound or released by anyone is perfected from the beginning, with no going or coming. Without any analysis, there exists no validation. Without base or root, this abides as empty clarity. This mind that abides as self-cognizance is liberated by the key points, so there is no bias. Liberated from time restrictions, there is no basis to rely upon. Liberated without effort, there is no need for diligence. Liberated through confidence, there is no need to strive. These are explained as liberation through confidence. Liberated from the beginning, there is no basis for repetition. Liberated through oneself, there exists no antidote. Liberated through gazing, that which is seen vanishes. Being completely liberated, there is no exertion.

Dawai: Remember, we also utilize Dream Yoga in here, and sky gazing and things like that as long as people request them and they're at that level, definitely. You'll start to be able to see light rays and bindus and things like that that you could not see before. That's a good sign that you're ready for effortless abiding into phenomena.

> Liberation through the key point of seeing naked awareness, liberation of time restrictions based on the past and future, and liberation in natural placement free from effort are the three meanings of "liberation from limitation."

Dawai: Okay so you have liberation through the key point of seeing awareness, of time restrictions based on past and future---because you're in presence---and liberation and natural placement (stability) free from effort. So yeah, you don't need to do anything once you stabilize relatively well. And then as long as you stick with the sangha and the teachers, you will gain the confidence because you'll see it for yourself, and that's where the real confidence comes from. Don't try to create the confidence. If you don't have confidence, allow that to be in your awareness, and it will blossom into confidence. Go figure.

> If the four liberations based on confidence are included with this, there come to be five. The nature of naked awareness is primordially free from bondage and release. That is designated as "liberation"; but ultimately, there is no bondage, so the characteristic of liberation does not exist.

